@node Operation "Using the Program."

	@{b}USING THE PROGRAM@{ub}

Alarmist acts like a standard Amiga Commodity (most MUI programs are commodities by default). This means that it can load and hide itself from the user and be called up instantly at the click of a key. If you require further information on Commodity applications then please consult your Amiga Workbench manual.

The program uses standard tooltypes for storing its global settings. These are parameters set in the programs icon, from Workbench, that it looks for at run-time. Do not confuse saving the Settings and saving the Alarm data. Alarm event data is saved to a file of its own.

The program's interface consists of a Main Window with a list showing the current Alarms for the present day, and some buttons. The Config button will open another window with a page-group allowing you to edit the program's configuration.

Another window called the Event Log Window keeps a running list of messages that occur at different times.

Then there is the World Clock Window (optional) that shows clocks from around the world, updating every minute.  The list of clocks is user-configurable.

If you use are going to have Alarmist run programs as if they were run from Workbench, you will need Stephan Becker's 'WBStart.library.' (wbstart 2.2) The full archive can be obtained from Ami-net - 'wbstart.lha'

Also see @{"Special Note About Iconification" link SpecialNote}.
@endnode

@node AlarmList "The Alarm List."

	@{b}THE ALARM LIST@{ub}

Alarmist handles multiple alarm events which appear summarised in the Event list in the Main Window. Glancing at this informs  you of what events are lined up for the day.

To create a new Alarm, just click on the New button at the bottom of the list. The @{"Edit Window" link EditWindow} will open and you can create an event. 

You may alter the settings of each Alarm by activating the entry in the list and clicking the Edit button. This will bring up the same edit window. Alternatively you could just just double-click on the Alarm to edit it.

You can easily remove Alarms from the list by selecting all the ones you want to delete and clicking on the Remove button.

The Toggle button allows you to change the state of Alarms in the list. When an Alarm's name is shown italicised, it means that it is suspended and will NOT cause an alarm at its given time!

In the list you will see each event displayed with its Type, Time, and Name.
The Type of an Alarm is indicated by either an 'a' or 'o'. This informs you whether the Alarm was created in Alarmist or imported from the On-Time @{"On-Time" link RunningOnTime} list.

By pressing the DELETE key, while the Main Window is activated, the next Alarm to occur will become the active entry in the list.

You may drag-and-drop icons onto any of the Alarmist windows or its app-icon (when iconified). This is performed via a User-Configurable @{"ARexx Script" link DropScript}.
@endnode

@node DropScript "Drag and Drop Script"

	@{b}APPLICATION WINDOW/ICON - DROP SCRIPT@{ub}

When an Icon is dropped onto any of the Main Alarmist windows an ARexx script named 'Alarmist_DropObj.rexx' is called with its first argument being the name of the File that was dropped. You must indicate where this script is by manually setting the tooltype DROP_SCRIPT in the Alarmist program icon.

This ARexx script enables the user to specify exactly what is to be done with files that are dropped onto Alarmist. The default action of the script that is installed with Alarmist takes this filename and creates a new Alarm with the Execute string set to the file name of the item dropped. It then proceeds to open the Edit Window allowing you to make a few adjustments. This is useful if you need to run a program to remind yourself of something coming up, but of course you may tailor the script for your own specific use.

Like all scripts that are run from Alarmist, the invoked script has its host address set to the Alarmist port automatically. This way the script will know exactly who to send its messages to (see example).
@endnode

@node EditWindow "The Alarm Edit Window."

	@{b}ALARM EDIT WINDOW@{ub}

This window consists of a number of gadgets for editing Alarm events.

If you have just created an Alarm using the New function then this Alarm will take on the global defaults set in "ENV:Alarmist.default."

*NOTE: This window contains 'Context Menus.' One menu (right mouse button over the window) allows you to perform operations on all of the settings gadgets in the window. The other menu is called over any of the settings gadgets and only effects them individually. They enable you load to and save all or individual default settings for the gadgets (set in "ENV:Alarmist.default").

There are three main data groups for each Alarm.

@{b}1. The Event Name@{ub}

This string may contain up to 128 characters. Try and use simple but easily identifiable names. This enables you to see at a glance what the event is without having to read a short story. eg. If you are reminding yourself to watch a certain television program then you could perhaps use an event name of "TV: <program name>." instead of "Time to watch <program name> on TV."

   @{b}Pre-Warn@{ub}

Every Alarm can be given a pre-warning. This means that you will receive a warning of the Alarm before its official time. See @{"Warn Events" link Config_Events} for information on global settings.

The actual Warn event may occur up to 100 minutes before the actual Alarm. You may select the local Alarm Event or the Global Pre-Warn Event data to be used as the Pre-Warn Event. The actual time before the Alarm (in minutes) that the Pre-Warn will occur can be set individually for each Alarm. Alternatively you could just use the global Pre-Warn Time set in the @{"Configuration" link Config_Events}. 

Next to the Alarm Name at the top of the window are two gadgets used to set the Pre-Warn. The first gadget (cycle) allows you to choose the Pre-Warn event. You may choose Global, Local or off. Global refers to the Pre-Warn event set in the Configuration and Local refers to the current Alarm event. The second gadget (pop-up slider) is used to set the Pre-Warn time for the event. you may select Global or a number from 1 to 100. The Global setting uses the value set in the Configuration.

To clarify:
- If you don't want to be reminded of an Alarm before it occurs then set Warn to 'Off'.
- If you would like to be reminded of an Alarm using the Warn Event settings in the Configuration  then set the Warn to Global.
- If you want the Warn Event to consist of the actual current Alarm settings then set Warn to Local.
- If you have a common reminder time of 5 minutes then set the Warn time in the Configuration to 5 minutes and set your Alarm Event's Pre-Warn time to Global.
- If you need to be reminded of an Alarm at particular amount of minutes before hand then set the Pre-Warn time individually for that event.

@{b}2. The Alarm@{ub}

This is the core element of the event. The Alarm time is represented by a slider which displays the actual time inside its knob. It should be pointed out here that Alarmist events are minute accurate only. It seemed pointless and trivial to have Alarm times accurate to the second.

To the right of the Alarm time slider is a checkmark - Log Popup.
This causes the Event Log Window to popup when the Alarm occurs. If you have an Alarm that just simply sends out an ARexx command then you may not want the Log Window to open. Just leave the checkmark deselected and the window won't open. Alarms are always entered into the log regardless of this switch.

Underneath is the actual Alarm Event settings. There is an Event Specification Object which contains information on the event to be executed. You may choose from the following four types of events by setting the cycle gadget appropriately. 

@{fg highlight}CLI@{fg text}   - The string will be executed just as though you had typed it into  CLI/Shell (ie. ignores any associated icons.)
@{fg highlight}WB@{fg text}    - Stephan Becker's @{"WBStart.library" link Operation} will be used to execute the string as though it were being run from Workbench (ie. associated icon is taken into account.)
@{fg highlight}ARexx@{fg text} - The string will be be treated as an ARexx command - it will be sent to AREXX:. Therefore if you had typed in the name of an ARexx script, it would be executed. If you wanted to send a message to Alarmist then you must tell ARexx to Address Alarmist first. eg. "Address Alarmist appear" (Remember to place the string in double quotes if it contains more than one command!) When Alarmist calls the script it will pass the number of the Alarm in the list as an ARexx argument. This way you can easily find out information about the event in the script.
@{fg highlight}Talk@{fg text}  - Sends the string directly to the ARexx port 'TALK'. You should have previously run the script 'Everyday:Rexx/Talk_ARexxPort.rexx' (a good place to do this is in you s:user-startup').

You might use your favourite sample player to play an appropriate sample or you could use anything! Included with the Everyday Organiser system (of which Alarmist is part of) is a program called Talk by the same author. This program acts very much like the old Commodore "Say" program but with a load of extra functions like the ability to speak the current time. This way you could have Alarmist tell you about an Alarm by speaking the time and a description of the event - a novel way to remind you of something.

Another program called 'Sam' is provided that lets you play audio samples from Workbench.

Using the Test button will enable you to check your settings to see if they work ok. This is advisable because incorrect settings @{b}could@{ub} cause you to miss an event although Alarmist will generally alert you in other ways as well (depending on the situation).

@{b}3. The Snooze Function@{ub}

This is one of the major advantages of using Alarmist. Setting a Snooze on an Alarm means that you can be reminded after an event has occurred. This can happen a certain number of times after the original Alarm has occurred.

The Snooze Time value is set in Minutes and Seconds. This is the time between Snooze events. For example, you may have the Alarm set to remind you to watch a TV program but you are in the habit of ignoring or forgetting the Alarm after it has gone off: so you set a snooze time for 15 seconds. Now after the initial Alarm event, the Snooze event will occur every 15 seconds for a set number of times.

If a Snooze event occurs and there is no Snooze Event Specification, then the original Alarm Event is used.

The Repeat Times for a Snooze event can be set with the numeric button - Snoozes.  The range is from 1 to 99 and INFINITE. The infinite setting is handy for those times when you never want to forget something. Now this means that you're going to need some way of turning off the Snooze events or they will go on forever and become extremely hazardous to your mental health 8). Well Alarmist uses a standard Commodity Hot-Key for this. Look in the @{"Configuration" link Config_HotKeys} for more information on how to set this up.
Simply hit the appropriate Hot-Key and the Snooze event will cease. It will cease no matter what the Snooze Repeat value is. When a Snooze event is manually stopped, it will be entered into the Event Log.

NOTE: If an Alarm's Snooze is still active and another Alarm event occurs then the first snooze will *stop* automatically.

You may have any number of Alarm Edit Windows open at once (one for each Alarm). While you are editing an Alarm is it deactivated.
@endnode

@node ConfigWindow "Alarmist Configuration."

	@{b}ALARMIST CONFIGURATION@{ub}

The Configuration window may be accessed by selecting 'Config' from the main window or from its menus.

	@{"  " link Config_Clock}  Clock
	@{"  " link Config_Events}  Special Events
	@{"  " link Config_General}  General
	@{"  " link Config_Log}  Log
	@{"  " link Config_HotKeys}  Hot Keys

You may save these settings with the Load and Save Configuration Menus items located in the 'Settings' menu.

A tooltype called STARTUP_SCRIPT exists that enables you to specify an ARexx script that you would like executed at run-time. An example script can be found in the Everyday:Rexx drawer.

The user-configurable @{"ARexx Scripts" link ARexxScripts} are saved as ToolTypes in the Alarmist icon along with the rest of the global configuration (not Alarm events).
@endnode

@node Config_Clock "The Configuration Window"

	@{b}THE WORKBENCH CLOCK@{ub}

An alarm clock program cannot be complete without a visual clock of some sort. Alarmist provides you with a Locale based clock string that appears on your Workbench screen.

Whenever an Alarm is to occur sometime in the current day, a star (Asterix) will appear after the clock text. If you double-click on the clock text it will be replaced with the time of the next Alarm along with the hours and minutes until the event. You will not be able to perform this function if there are no more Alarms for the current day. A current List of Alarms could be made up of a mixture of On-Time and Alarmist events so we would have to recheck the OnTime event file for events tomorrow to accurately report information for that day. This would be beyond the scope of this program.

On the Clock Page you will see a variety of options that allow you to customize your clock settings.

@{b}Update Time:@{ub}

This refers to the time intervals between clock updates. This allows you to minimize CPU loading with larger Update Times. Alarmist will not load up the CPU a great deal but you can experiment with this setting if you like. It is important to note that this setting also affects when Alarmist checks for Alarm and Snooze Events. If you want your Alarm events to occur exactly on the minute then I suggest you use an Update Time of 1 second. An Update Time of 15 seconds and a Snooze time of 5 seconds doesn't make much sense either. It is recommended to leave the Update Time at around 1 to 5 seconds. But you could change this, like most commands, via @{"ARexx" link RX_UpdateTime}.

@{b}Active:@{ub}

This is just an on/off switch for the clock. It doesn't deactivate Alarmist, it just stops the clock from being displayed. The Alarm mechanism isn't affected.

@{b}Clock Format:@{ub}

This string gadget allows you to change what the Clock Display shows. The clock uses standard Locale date/time formatting. See @{"Clock Formatting" link ClockFormatting}.

@{b}Text: Back:@{ub}

These two cycle gadgets let you change the text and background colours of your clock. This is only a temporary measure and is not extremely useful at the moment!

@{b}Clock XY:@{ub}

This checkmark allows you to lock the position of the clock display on the screen. If it is selected then the clock is locked to a certain position on the screen. If it is deselected then you may click on the clock text and move it round like you would a normal window. In fact the clock is a window; it just has all the normal window parts hidden. So you can move the clock around to any position on the screen and then lock it in position. The default position is on the Workbench menu bar just left of the screen cycle gadget. You may return the clock to this position by clicking on the @{b}Reset XY@{ub} button.

@{b}Font:@{ub}

This popup gadget allows you to specify what font the Clock Display will use. You may use the pop-up asl font requester or you can specify the font by typing in the name followed by a '/' and the size of the font. When you press return, Alarmist will attempt to load the font. If the font cannot be loaded or you have entered a blank entry then it will revert to the default screen font.

NOTE: The fact that the Clock is actually a window means that Intuition will not be allowed to fully reset itself when you change a Workbench preference setting like ScreenMode unless the Clock Window closes. Some clock programs just simply blit (copy) the clock directly onto the Workbench screen. This means that it can easily disappear. For example; if it was on the screen menu bar and the a menu is used then it would disappear until next clock update. Since Alarmist uses a window for its clock then it will always be there unless another window covers it. So if you ever see the message "Intuition is attempting to reset the Workbench screen. Please close all windows, except drawers." and all windows appear closed then it is probably the Alarmist clock because it is still open. This can be easily resolved in a number of ways!
 
1 - Click on the Clock as you would a window, to activate it, and then press the ESCAPE key on the keyboard. The Clock will now disappear and Intuition will be allowed to reset Workbench.
 2 - Pop-up the Alarmist interface and turn the clock off as shown above.
 3 - Disable Alarmist via the standard Workbench Commodity Exchange program and the clock will also disappear.
 4 - Send an @{"ARexx Command" link RX_Clock} to turn the clock display off.

Its a small price to pay for the clock to be visible all the time.

NOTE: If you have Stefan Becker's ScreenNotify Library installed then Alarmist will use this library to attempt to close its Clock window when Intuition resets. This doesn't seem to be too efficient at the moment and you may still get the standard requester asking you to close all windows. In this case just hit retry. It may happen more than once. This library does not work on all computer setups but it is very handy indeed!

@{b}Public Screen:@{ub}

You may set the Public Screen on which the Clock appears. This isn't too user friendly at the moment but will probably improve in later versions. You could write a script to use one of the freely available CLI programs that get the name of the frontmost public screen and send an @{"ARexx command" link RX_ClockPubScreen} to Alarmist to change the clock screen. In future versions it may follow public screens (when I work it out 8). 
@endnode

@node Config_Events "The Configuration Window"

	@{b}SPECIAL EVENT SETTINGS@{ub}

This page of settings deals with two extra type of events: Chime and Warn.

@{b}Chime Events.@{ub}

Selecting the check mark enables the Chime. At the beginning of every hour the Chime function will execute the event specified with the Event Specification Gadgets. You may set the actual hours that the chime will function with the From and To slider gadgets underneath.

The supplied ARexx Script 'Alarmist_Chime.rexx' gives an example of using ARexx for a Chime Event.

@{b}Warn Events@{ub}

Normally when an Alarm occurs, it will give you no previous warning unless you change the Alarm time to just before the actual time of the event. This is one option but it may get confusing if you can't remember whether you set the Alarm for the actual time or just before it: so the Warn option gives you a reminder facility.

It has the usual checkmark gadget to Activate it and the Event Specification Gadgets. Below this is the Pre-Warn time. This is the time (in minutes) that you would like to be reminded before each Alarm occurs. At the moment you will only be reminded *once* at the exact Pre-Warn time before the event. This may change in later versions but it has not yet been decided.

You may do tricky things by executing an ARexx Script on Warn Events that could do a variety of things like finding out what Alarm will occur next. See the provided ARexx script 'Everyday:rexx/Alarmist_Warn.rexx' for an example of this. It is recommended that you use this script.

There are two types of Warn Events that can be set when editing or creating an @{"Alarm event" link EditWindow}.
@endnode

@node Config_General "The Configuration Window"

	@{b}GENERAL SETTINGS@{ub}

This is the final page that allows you set some general preference options.

@{b}Main Window PopUp:@{ub}

This switch causes the main window to 'pop up' when the program loads. This could be useful if you wish to scan the list for events upon loading.

@{b}Main Gadgets:@{ub}

Some people may wish to leave the Main Window open. This way you will always see the current list of events by glancing at the window. These sort of people will most probably have a large screen resolution and Workbench space for lease. The Main Gadgets switch lets you decide whether the buttons on the Main Window will be displayed or not. Leaving them out will mean that the window won't require as much space, or you'll have more space for the Event List as it will be the only object displayed.

@{b}Confirm Remove:@{ub}

Activates user confirmation requests when Removing Alarms from the list.

@{b}Daylight Savings:@{ub}

This cycle gadget tells Alarmist whether the time it reads from the computer is in @{"Daylight Savings" link DaylightSavings time}. This means that the clock is one hour ahead of normal local time. This setting is used when Alarmist calculates Greenwich Mean Time from the internal clock. See @{"World Clock Window" link WorldClockWindow}.

@{b}GMT Offset:@{ub}

This numeric pop-button allows you to set your local offset from Greenwich Mean Time (in minutes). This is a little bit "non-standard" but it allows for possible changes in Country Time-Zones. Like other configuration settings, this setting is loaded via an Icon Tooltype. If this Tooltype is not found then Alarmist will use the GMT Offset as indicated by your Workbench Locale settings.
@endnode

@node Config_Log "The Configuration Window"

	@{b}LOG WINDOW SETTINGS@{ub}

This page enables you to set certain attributes for the Log Window.

The group "Popup Log on" allows you to set the requirements for the Log Window to popup automatically on a reload. When a reload takes place either at run-time or midnight, Alarmist will check these attributes along with the data in the Log to see whether it needs to popup the window.

· Reminders: Popup the Log if there are entries in the Reminder Log or there are any Events For Today Reminders.
· Tasks: Popup the Log if there are entries in the Tasks For Today Log.
· Previous: Popup the Log if there were previous Alarms that day. 

If you turn off all these switches then the Log window will now appear when a reload takes place. It is suggested that you at least leave the Reminders switch on, otherwise you might not get notified of future or current Events and that would be tragic! So be careful!

@{b}Clear at Midnight:@{ub}

Lets say you are running a bulletin board and therefore you leave your computer turned on all the time. If you are running Alarmist with @{"On-Time©" link RunningOnTime} then after a while you may end up with a huge list of Alarms in the Log looking rather messy. Well, with this option selected you can have the Log List cleared at midnight.
@endnode

@node Config_HotKeys "The Configuration Window"

	@{b}COMMODITY KEY SETTINGS@{ub}

This page contains all the Commodity key strings for operation of Alarmist.

· Pop Key  Hot-Key that brings up the Alarmist interface.
· Snooze Stop Key Hot-Key that allows you to stop a Snooze event.
· Log Key Hot-Key that opens and closes the @{"Log Window" link LogWindow}.
· World Clock Key" Hot-Key that opens and closes the @{"World Clock Window" link WorldClockWindow}.

They all take standard Commodity key description strings.
@endnode

@node RunningOnTime "Running On-Time©"

	@{b}USING ALARMIST© WITH ON-TIME©@{ub}

As stated in the @{"introduction" link About}, Alarmist was originally designed to operate alongside the program On-Time. This way Alarmist can alert you of Events every day. It performs  this by reloading the standard On-Time list file "ENV:OnTime.list" at 12:00 AM (midnight) every morning (of course you must have your computer switched on ;-) and looks for any events occurring on the new day and inserts them into its list. Alarmist will also alert you of Events that don't have specific times, remind you of future Events and display Tasks for the day (refer to ON-Time documentation).

Together, Alarmist and On-Time make a great team. You can use Alarmist by itself or you could use it together with On-Time for maximum advantage. Lets say you had just switched on your computer and needed to do something but you had an engagement later on that you didn't want to miss. If it was a one-off event and didn't re-occur then you could just simply pop-up the Alarmist interface via the Hot-Key and enter the event. This way you wouldn't have to load On-Time and enter it indirectly. You could even make up an @{"ARexx" link ARexxCommands} script to do most of the work for you (see example script provided). 

It's all up to you how you manage the programs.

Now you may might ask:

What happens if Alarmist loads the OnTime.list file and inserts an Alarm for an Event and then I select Save from Alarmist? Doesn't Alarmist save this new Alarm along with the others in its own file 'ENV:Alarmist.list' ?"

The answer to this question is no! Alarmist is intelligent enough to make a note of On-Time events that it has inserted into its list and leaves them out of its own event file.

Everytime you load an Alarmist list it searches for the "ENV:OnTime.list" as well and if it is found then it is examined as well. This way you will always have an up-to-date list. Alarmist uses one of the really powerful features of AmigaDOS to enhance this - file notification. Whenever the "ENV:OnTime.list" gets changed Alarmist will get a message saying that it's time to reload the OnTime.list. This displays the true power of using these two programs (and the Amiga) together.

Just a quick note. Make sure you read the On-Time documentation if you are going to use that program.
@endnode

@node FileManagement "Loading and Saving Lists"

	@{b}LOADING AND SAVING LISTS@{ub}

It is important to realise where and how the default Alarmist list is saved and how On-Time Events are treated.

By default, Alarmist acts like a standard preferences program, in that it saves its list file to the ENV: and ENVARC: drawers. When you select Use from the Main Window, the current list will be saved to the ENV: drawer (in RAM:Env). Selecting Save will save the list to the ENV: and ENVARC: (SYS:Prefs/Env-Archive) drawers. For more information on this -  see your Amiga Workbench manuals.

You may choose to load an Alarmist list from a different location with either the Project- Open menu or with the @{"ARexx Open" link RX_Open} command. NOTE: When you perform a standard Load, the global @{"OnTime" link RunningOnTime} list will be examined.

From the Project menu and from the @{"ARexx Open" link RX_Open} command you may Merge-load and Alarmist list. This opens a specific Alarmist file and inserts its contents into the current list without clearing the list. So all the merging takes place in the current list and nothing is saved until you issue that command. NOTE: When you are merge-loading an Alarmist file, the global @{"On-Time" link RunningOnTime} list will *NOT* be examined. To do this would cause problems with the previous list in memory and cause glitches in the fabric of space.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} When saving a list you must remember that *ONLY* Alarmist events will be saved (those events created with Alarmist and not imported from On-Time). So if you alter an On-Time Alarm from within Alarmist then select Save, the changes are not kept. To save the On-Time Alarms would be meaningless as they are created and changed from their parent program. Also, if you were to reload the Alarm list from within Alarmist or simply perform a Last Saved command then the On-Time event(s) will be restored to their original state as saved in the On-Time Event file. Altering On-Time Alarm Events from within Alarmist should be only treated as a temporary measure. Remember that the Alarm may not be present in the Alarmist list the next day as Alarmist will only import On-Time Events that occur on the present day. And the list gets reloaded at midnight.

Now just a small mention of something important. Don't confuse the Save and Use buttons on the Main Window with the Load Config and Save Config options from the Settings menu. The latter refers only to the Clock, Chime and general settings which get saved as Icon tooltypes. The buttons on the main window are used only to save the current Alarmist List in memory. So don't go hitting the Save button when you want to save the clock settings!
@endnode

@node LogWindow "The Event Log Window"

	@{b}THE EVENT LOG WINDOW@{ub}

The Log Window is a separate window that contains a read-only list of  messages. Everytime an event of some kind occurs within Alarmist a message will be added into the Event Log List.

There can be three separate lists in this window: Log, Task, Reminder list. The first two may not always be shown. They will be hidden if they contain no information.

@{b}The Event Log List @{ub}

This list is used by Alarmist to let the user know of previous Alarms that occurred before it loaded and other things such as when Alarms occur.

The first message in the list will @{i}always@{ui} indicate when Alarmist was activated. This is the exact time that Alarmist was loaded.

Various messages such as Alarm events and Snooze stops are recorded in the list.

Whenever Alarmist is activated or deactivated via the Workbench Commodity Exchange program then this will also we record in the log.

The Log List can be @{"cleared" link ClearingEventLog} by using the 'Clear Log' function from the menu.

@{b}The Reminder List@{ub}

This list is used to inform the user of On-Time Events that will occur in future days. For a full explanation of Events with Reminders, please see the On-Time documentation.

The Reminders will be shown with their begin date, Name and Notes. After the date you will see a number prefixed with a plus sign '+'. This lets you know how many days till that event. If the event has a duration of more than 1 day, you will see the number of days enclosed in sqaure brackets, e.g. '[2]'. So you could endup with a reminder: '28 August 1996[2] +6 Do: Fix WEB page'

@{b}The Tasks for Today  List@{ub}

Alarmist will display all On-Time Tasks that intersect or occur on the present day in this list. This way you can get a quick idea of any important things that need to be done without loading On-Time. For a full explanation of Tasks, please see the On-Time documentation.

** You may double-click on entries in the 'Reminder' and 'Tasks for Today' list. This will then run an ARexx script called 'Alarmist_OnTimeEdit.rexx' This script has been set up to automatically allow you to edit that item in On-Time. It just provides a quick link to that item in On-Time.

The Log Window can be made to appear and disappear via a Hot-Key. See @{"Configuration" link Config_HotKeys}.
@endnode

@node ClearingEventLog "Clearing the Event Log List"

	@{b}CLEARING THE EVENT LOG LIST@{ub}

Sometimes the Event Log List can get messy as a number of messages build up. This option allows you to clear the list of old data.

If you wish you can have the list cleared everytime an event file is loaded. See @{"Config Page" link ConfigPage}.

All the lines of messages will be deleted except for one. The first entry will remain because it indicates when Alarmist was first activated (when it loaded).
@endnode

@node WorldClockWindow "The World Clock Window."

	@{b}THE WORLD CLOCK WINDOW@{ub}

The World Clock Window is used to display a variety of different times from around the world. Like the Log Window, it can be opened and closed via a @{"Hot-Key" link Config_HotKeys}.  It contains a list of user-configurable clocks from around the world that are updated every minute.

In the drawer "Everyday:WorldClocks" you'll find a number of different World Clock Definition files. They are named "WorldClocks_xxxx", where "xxxx" represents a language. When Alarmist runs, it scans through the System Locale languages and tries to find a World Clock file for the preferred language(s).

See @{"Creating and Editing the World Clock Data File" link WorldClockDataFile}.

In the World Clock Window, each Clock will appear next to its respective name. If the time is prefixed with a '-' this means that it's the day before and a '+' indicates the day after your local day. An asterix '*' indicates that the location is in Daylight Savings time.

@{b}Using a Different Location and Time@{ub}

Normally Alarmist will use the local time (computer's time) and GMT difference when calculating the list of clocks, but you may choose otherwise. Let's say you wanted to find out what time it would be in Barbados when it is 4:00pm in London. This is easy to accomplish. You may select an entry in the list of World Clocks to become the "Local Time." This means that the selected entry becomes the local time instead of using the computer's clock to get the GMT difference and the current time.

To select another location, Double-Click with the left moust button on an entry in the World Clocks list. Two gadgets will now appear at the top of the Window. One will display the name of the city activated in the list and the other allows you to select a local time (Standard EO Time Object - refer On-Time docs). So, in our example above, we would first double-click on "London" in the list. After the gadgets appeared at the top of the window we can then change the time to 4:00pm. Now all the entries in the list are redisplayed using this new local time. So scan down the list until you get to Barbados and there you'll have the time in Barbados when it is 4:00pm in London. All the clocks are displayed relative to the location and time at the top of the window.

You may now click on any other entry (once) to become the local time.

When you are in this mode, where you select a different local time, the list will not be updated every minute because you are setting the time manually at the top of the window.

To go back to the original mode that the World Clocks Window opens up in, you simply have to press the "Delete" key while the window is active. The two gadets at the top of the window will disappear and the list of World Clocks will be displayed relative to the computer's location and current time. It will also return back to the mode where it is updated every minute. The "Delete" key will toggle these two modes.
@endnode

@node WorldClockDataFile "The World Clock Window."

	@{b}CREATING AND EDITING THE WORLD CLOCK DATA FILE@{ub}

To define a list of clocks, do the following:

· Load the WorldClock file of your language into a normal text editor and create or edit a number of clock entries. Each line represents an entry in the World Clock List and is comprised of a City Name, Local deviation from Greenwich Mean Time (GMT) in minutes, and a number from 0 to 4 indicating a @{"Daylight Savings" link DaylightSavings} setting.

   eg.   Adelaide|-570|0
         Chicago|360|2
         London|0|0

A Daylight Savings setting of 0 (zero) means "off", 1 means "on", 2 = Auto North, 3 = Auto South, and 4 = Auto Europe.

The City Names can be up to 50 characters long and *must* be separated from their GMT differences and Daylight Savings setting using a '|').

· Save this file to the same place where you found it, e.g "Everyday:WorldClocks/WorldClocks_xxxx".

You may have any number of entries in the file but remember that it takes more time to update many entries, but it's not too significant as it only happens once every minute.  The clocks are only updated when they are displayed, and then, once every minute.

You may temporarily hide an entry in the list by placing a semi-colin ';' before the entry in the data file.

Each clock entry in the data file will @{b}not@{ub} be sorted into alphabetical order in the World Clock Window. Each entry is inserted in the order that it was loaded from the file. This is so you can customise the ordering to your own tastes. Of course you could sort them alphabetically by using the AmigaDOS Sort command on the World Clocks data file (See AmigaDOS manual).

Alarmist first calculates your local GMT set in the @{"Configuration" link Config_General}. Then each Clock is displayed in reference to its own deviation from GMT.

It is important to let Alarmist know if you are in Daylight Savings time by setting the switch in the @{"Configuration" link GeneralPage}. If indicated, then Alarmist will subtract one hour from the computer's clock before calculating each World Clock time. Alarmist will display an entry with regard to its predefined Daylight Savings setting which it found in the data file. When an entry is shown using with a "*" it means that it is using a Daylight Savings time.
@endnode

@node ClockFormatting "The Configuration Window"

	@{b}SETTING THE CLOCK TEXT FORMAT@{ub}

The Workbench clock built into Alarmist uses the standard Locale time formatting facilities built into the Amiga's operating system. See your Workbench manual if you wish to know more about the System Locale.

Alarmist comes with a standard clock format but if you're into changing things then you can use the following parameters to make your clock look different.
  
	%a - abbreviated weekday name
	%A - weekday name
	%b - abbreviated month name
	%B - month name
	%c - same as "%a %b %d %H:%M:%S %Y"
	%C - same as "%a %b %e %T %Z %Y"
	%d - day number with leading 0s
	%D - same as "%m/%d/%y"
	%e - day number with leading spaces
	%h - abbreviated month name
	%H - hour using 24-hour style with leading 0s
	%I - hour using 12-hour style with leading 0s
	%j - julian date
	%m - month number with leading 0s
	%M - the number of minutes with leading 0s
	%p - AM or PM strings
	%q - hour using 24-hour style
	%Q - hour using 12-hour style
	%r - same as "%I:%M:%S %p"
	%R - same as "%H:%M"
	%S - number of seconds with leadings 0s
	%t - insert a tab character
	%T - same as "%H:%M:%S"
	%U - week number, taking Sunday as first day of week
	%w - weekday number
	%W - week number, taking Monday as first day of week
	%x - same as "%m/%d/%y"
	%X - same as "%H:%M:%S"
	%y - year using two digits with leading 0s
	%Y - year using four digits with leading 0s

The default setting is %A %d-%b-%y, %Q:%M:%S %p
@endnode

@node SpecialNote "A Special Note About Iconification."

	@{b}A SPECIAL NOTE ABOUT ICONIFICATION@{ub}

The MUI system allows you to iconify applications in a number of ways like window buttons and hot-keys. When an application is iconified, all its windows are closed and the application is temporarily 'put to sleep.' This works well with most programs but not with Alarmist.

For most of the time, you may want to leave a window open or open one window without the other. If you were to iconify Alarmist then the Main Window, Log Window and World Clock Window would disappear, and this isn't too useful. Therefore, Alarmist allows you to choose which windows are to remain open at any given time without having to Iconify the program (in the MUI sense) . Alarmist has hot-keys for opening and closing the Main Window, Log Window and World Clock window. This means you can close each window without quiting the program.

So there should NEVER be any need to iconify Alarmist using MUI. In fact, it might be a good idea to remove the Iconify window button from the Alarmist windows using the MUI prefs program.
@endnode

@node DaylightSavings "About Daylight Savings"

	@{b}DAYLIGHT SAVINGS@{ub}

Alarmist allows you to tell it whether you or another country is using Daylight Savings time.

There are a few world standards for when a country or state should use Daylight Savings time.

1.  @{b}Auto North@{ub} Used by most of North America.
    Begin: first Sunday in April of 4.
    End:   last Sunday in October.

2.  @{b}Auto South@{ub} Used by most countries in southern Hemisphere.
    Begin: last Sunday in October.
    End:   first Sunday in March.

3.  @{b}Auto Europe@{ub} Used by most European countries.
    Begin: last Sunday in March.
    End:   last Sunday in September.

If you use one of these three settings then Alarmist will automatically work out when a country is in Daylight Savings time, otherwise you can set them on or off manually.

@endnode

@node KnownBugs "Those Lovely Things"

	@{b}KNOWN BUGS IN ALARMIST@{ub}

- Alarmist will reset itself at midnight when it loads-up the day's events. This means that any Snooze events will cease...you have to wake up sooner or later 8).
- Snooze events will also be deactivated when accepting changes on any Alarm in the Alarm Edit Window or adding a new event. When something changes in the Event list or something new is added, Alarmist has to recheck everything, thereby clearing the current event status. I might get around this in the future sometime if I can think of a strategy that doesn't have any worse side-effects.

- Veritas est nimis involuta ingeniis hominum.
@endnode

@node Future "In the Future..."

	@{b}MAYBE IN THE FUTURE...@{ub}

- I could do a lot more things to the Clock Display to make it more interesting. If anyone has some code that they would like me to use then feel free to send it to me for consideration. Remember, this is Giftware.
One possible solution which could be interesting is to have a set of Public Classes. Each class/library would be a different type of clock and the user could select which one to use. This way you don't take up room in the main program with loads of code that isn't necessary. An idea that I will look at in the future. Remembering, of course, that all MUI Public Classes have to be registered. Different MUI applications could make use of these classes as well, but not all of them would need a facility to display the next occurring alarm.
- Any suggestions?
@endnode

@node History "History"

· @{b}v1.50@{ub} - Sixth Release (1st April 1997)

   @{fg highlight}Fixes@{fg text}
   - 'Auto South' calculation was on vacation in some alternate universe.

   @{fg highlight}World Clocks@{fg text}
   - You may now select a location and time from the list of World Clocks as the Local time instead of using the computer's location and time. See @{"World Clock Window" link WorldClockWindow} documentation for full description.
   - List entries are now drag-sortable for temporary effect.
   - Now using standard convention where numbers west of GMT are negative and east is positive. Note: the WorldClocks data file is now updated..
   - GMT Differences now displayed in hours and minutes, instead of just minutes.
   - 205 Cities added to the standard World Clock Data File.

   @{fg highlight}Log Window@{fg text}
   - The General Log List has been moved to the top of the Low Window for prominence.
   - You may now double-click on entries in the 'Reminder' and 'Tasks for Today' lists. This has the effect of invoking the new ARexx script 'Everyday:rexx/Alarmist_OnTimeEdit.rexx' to enable you to edit the item in On-Time. Thanks to ARexx!!!!

   @{fg highlight}Miscellaneous@{fg text}
   - Added @{"GMT Offset" link Config_General} setting in Configuration.
   - 100% recompiled with SAS/C 6.57.
   - Pressing the Help key now goes straight to the relevant section in the documentation rather than the Contents.
   - Event execution (ie. CLI, WB, AREXX) enhanced. Also now uses Stephan Becker's WBStart.library (wbstart 2.2) to launch WB programs instead of the ancient 1.4 system.
   - Introduced a new @{"Execution Type" link EditWindow} - "Talk" in the Event Specification. 

   @{fg highlight}ARexx@{fg text}
   - Sending Mechansism re-writen. Number of ARexx messages executing at once is now unlimited.
   - Run-time dynamically installable User ARexx @{"Menus" link ARexxScripts}.
   - @{"RX" link RX_RX} Redefined.
   
   @{fg highlight}Obsolete Tooltypes@{fg text}
   - AREXX_SCRIPT_1, AREXX_SCRIPT_2, AREXX_SCRIPT_3, AREXX_SCRIPT_4
   
-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.40@{ub} - Fifth Release (9th December 1996)

   @{fg highlight}World Clocks@{fg text}
   - The World Clock data file has been redesigned, so take another look at @{"how to set it up" link WorldClock}.
   - GMT Time Zone Difference now displayed (in minutes).
   - Whole window is disposed of when not open. This will conserve some memory.

   @{fg highlight}Miscellaneous@{fg text}
   - You may now set the local Daylight Savings setting to On, Off, Auto North, Auto South or Auto Europe, in the @{"Configuration" link GeneralPage}.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.30@{ub} - Fourth Release (31st August 1996)

   @{fg highlight}Fixes@{fg text}
   - Was causing Enforcer Hits when selecting Edit and NO Alarm was active in the list (reported by  Mario Kemper).
   - Was causing Enforcer Hits when the Clock Window was NOT active and the application was de-activated via Exchange (reported by Mario Kemper).
   - Fixed the Clean Log On Reload option as it wasn't working 100% correctly.
   - Fixed a couple of catalog definitions that were messing up.

   @{fg highlight}Alarms@{fg text}
   - Individual Pre-Warn times can now be set for each @{"Alarm" link EditWindow} (optional). This has meant major reconstructional changes in the way Alarmist deals with Pre-Warn events because now the next occuring active Alarm may not necessarily be the next Warn event!

   @{fg highlight}Miscellaneous@{fg text}
   - Program can now cope with multiple Alarm or Warn events that occur on the same minute. Previously it was ignoring everyone except the first on a particular minute (Bah! 8).
   - Program now behaves like a commodity and Pops Up Main Window when you try to run it twice.
   - Renamed CX PopUp configuration switch to Main Window Popup for technical correctness.
   - You can now set the draw pens for the Clock Window up to 255. Still not particularly useful, but it helps.
   - Added new page 'Log' in Configuration. You can now specify requirements for the Log Window to popup.
   - Changed World Clocks list scroller to a right-edge window scroller. Let me know if you don't like it.
   
   @{fg highlight}ARexx@{fg text}
   - When Alarmist calls an ARexx script from either a Warn or Alarm event it will pass the number of the Alarm in the list that caused the event as an ARexx argument. This can be used to find out information about the caller event. (see 'Everyday:rexx/Alarmist_Warn.rexx').
   - The script 'Everyday:rexx/Alarmist_Warn.rexx' has been altered slightly for the new Pre-Warn system. You might also want to take a look at the new script 'Alarmist_NextAlarm.rexx'.
   - @{"GetNextWarn" link RX_GetNextWarn} added
   - @{"Update" link RX_Update} redefined.
   - Appear and Disappear commands removed and replaced with @{"MainWindow" link RX_MainWindow} for technical correctness and consitency.

   - Various minor changes here and there.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.21@{ub} - Patch Release (14th June 1996)

   - Some weekday names were not corresponding to the correct weekday in some countries (reported by Ronald Vermeulen).

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.20@{ub} - Third Release (8th June 1996)

   - ** Major changes to enable co-operation with On-Time version 2 (see On-Time documentation).
   - Program completely cataloged. Phew, what a job! 8).
   - The file "Alarmist_World.data", that used to reside in the same directory as Alarmist was run from, is now obsolete. The directory Everyday:WorldClocks now holds this language sensitive file. 
   - Inactive Alarms now have their names italicised in the main list instead of indicating 'on' or 'off' in a seperate column.
   - Added Alarm Copy function (and ARexx equivalent). This could have easily been performed via ARexx but some people are either too lazy, can't use it or forget they own an Amiga 8).
   - Added Trigger ARexx command because I got bored one day.
   - Made allowance for dos.library ReadArgs() bug that requires lines to be '\n' terminated. That'll teach me for not reading the autodocs thoroughly!
   - Removed the TOGGLE/S option from ARexx commands. It is now a default (as if should have been). 
   - Added Requester ARexx command.
   - Added artificial intelligence performance algorithm to wake you up when you fall asleep at the key board ........only joking 8).

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

· @{b}v1.10@{ub} - Second Release (27th March 1996)

   - Fixed numerous Enforcer Hits 8).
   - Functions-Log menu wasn't connected (oops).
   - Settings-Create Icons menu wasn't updating after a Load Config.
   - ARexx Menu update problem fixed.
   - Chime and Warn execution groups now use the Execution Group Class that is used in the Alarm Edit Windows. This should have been done in the first release because it makes a load of sense! If you're going to make classes then you should use them 8).
   - Added 'LogMessage' ARexx command.
   - Altered template for ARexx command @{"GetField" link RX_GetField} from 'NUMBER/N' to 'ENTRY/N/K,NUMBER/N'
   - Altered numeric displays for some slider gadgets in the Config Window.
   - Added a quick Startup stack check.
   - Added template for CLI loading.
   - Fixed CON: de-allocation for ARexx messages.
   - Tampered with Exec Group drag & drop so you can't drag them onto themselves or other Exec Groups with the same attribute values.
   - Added 'DROP_SCRIPT' icon tooltype.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------

@{b}v1.0@{ub} - Original Release (8th February 1996)

@endnode


@remark ************************************************************
@remark                   ARexx Commands Start Here
@remark ************************************************************

@node ARexxScripts

	@{b}USER CONFIGURABLE AREXX SCRIPTS@{ub}

Alarmist allows you to execute external ARexx scripts from within the program. In which case you must have ARexx operational on your system (refer Amiga manuals). Alarmist will not execute the scripts itself but tell ARexx to perform the scripts (standard procedure). The essential difference is that the default Host Port for the script will be Alarmist.

In the ARexx pull-down menu you will find the following items.

@{b}Run New Script...@{ub}

A file requester will open. Select an ARexx script and close the requester. The file will be executed as an ARexx script.

@{b}Run Last Script@{ub}

This calls the script previously invoked with the 'Run New Script' menu command. If no ARexx script exists then a file requester will open.

@{b}User Definable ARexx Menus@{ub}

Below these two menu items you may install pre-defined ARexx scripts with individual menu-shortcuts. At run-time Alarmist looks for the file 'Everyday:Alarmist.ARexxMenu' and scans it for names of scripts to install in the menu. Refer to instructions contained within the file.
@endnode

@node ARexxCommands "Controlling Alarmist with ARexx."

	@{b}ALARMIST AREXX COMMAND SET@{ub}

Only one version of Alarmist can be running at once and its ARexx port is ALARMIST

Apart from the standard MUI ARexx commands (see MUI Documentation), Alarmist has the following commands. Any errors will be reported in the RC variable (0 = success, any other value indicates an error).

See also: @{"Special Note on Iconification" link SpecialNote}.

You can install user-defined @{"ARexx Menu scripts" link ARexxScripts} for easy reference as well.

